DESCRIPTION
Pure SelectCohort: walk refs/etude/runs/*, filter to runs with the named stage that is replayable (recorded git_sha + inline-content inputs + an output artifact), order by manifest Created DESC, take --last N, report skipped/non-qualifying runs. Library-only, no CLI. Table-tested. First shippable slice of decomposed etude-bench-command.

DESIGN
## Plan (sub-bead .1 — cohort selection ONLY; library, no CLI/replay/eval) [attempt 2]

**Attempt-2 change (gate finding, incorporated):** the git_sha eligibility check is
no longer "non-empty" — it is now SYNTACTIC OID VALIDITY. See "Eligibility predicate"
step 2 and the new `invalid-git-sha` skip reason. Everything else the gate confirmed
sound is unchanged.

**Scope boundary:** Pure `SelectCohort` library in a NEW `internal/bench` package.
NO CLI, NO replay execution, NO eval. It only ENUMERATES + FILTERS + ORDERS stored
runs and reports what is eligible vs skipped. The pipeline (.2) and CLI (.4) consume
its output. It does no git checkout and invokes no runner/judge.

**Approach:** Walk `refs/etude/runs/*` exactly as `run list` does
(internal/cli/run.go:73-94): `store.List(ctx, "refs/etude/runs")` (no trailing
slash), strip the `refs/etude/runs/` prefix for the run id, `store.ReadFile(ctx,
ref, "manifest.json")`, `runmanifest.ParseJSON`. For each run, find the named stage
and test the SAME replayability predicate replay enforces. Order qualifying runs by
`Manifest.Created` DESC, take first N. Skipped runs are recorded with a reason, never
errored.

**Signature + types (designed for .2/.4 consumers):**

    package bench
    const runsPrefix = "refs/etude/runs/"

    func SelectCohort(ctx context.Context, store refstore.Store, stage string, last int) (CohortResult, error)

    type CohortResult struct {
        Stage    string         // echoed stage name
        Selected []CohortRun    // qualifying, Created DESC, len <= last
        Skipped  []SkippedRun   // non-qualifying, in enumeration (ref) order
    }
    type CohortRun struct {
        RunID   string                  // run id (ref suffix)
        Commit  string                  // resolved run-ref commit OID (snapshot pin)
        Stage   runmanifest.Stage       // the matched stage (carries GitSHA, Inputs, Output, Producer)
        Created time.Time               // manifest Created (for ordering / display)
    }
    type SkippedRun struct {
        RunID  string
        Reason SkipReason
        Detail string   // human note, e.g. "input \"context\" is a pointer artifact"
    }
    type SkipReason string
    const (
        SkipStageMissing   SkipReason = "stage-missing"     // stage name not present
        SkipStageAmbiguous SkipReason = "stage-ambiguous"   // stage name appears >1x
        SkipNoGitSHA       SkipReason = "no-git-sha"         // GitSHA empty
        SkipInvalidGitSHA  SkipReason = "invalid-git-sha"    // GitSHA non-empty but not a valid OID
        SkipPointerInput   SkipReason = "pointer-input"      // an input Storage != content
        SkipPointerOutput  SkipReason = "pointer-output"     // output Storage != content
    )

Rationale — CohortRun carries the whole `runmanifest.Stage` plus `Commit`: .2 needs
exactly the inputs `replay.ResolveInputs`/`replay.go` consume (GitSHA, Inputs roles+
storage, Output role+media-type, Producer for overrides), and `Commit` pins the
snapshot. Re-resolving by run-id later would risk TOCTOU; passing the stage + commit
forward keeps the cohort a consistent snapshot and lets .2 call ResolveInputs (or read
the commit directly) without re-deciding eligibility.

**Eligibility predicate (faithful to what replay can ACTUALLY replay):**
A run qualifies iff its manifest parses AND the named stage:
 1. occurs exactly once (0 -> SkipStageMissing; >1 -> SkipStageAmbiguous; mirrors
    replay.ResolveInputs case 0/default at resolve.go:102-128),
 2. has a SYNTACTICALLY VALID git OID in `GitSHA`: non-empty AND (len==40 OR len==64)
    AND all lowercase hex. Empty -> SkipNoGitSHA; non-empty-but-malformed -> SkipInvalidGitSHA.
    [ATTEMPT-2 CHANGE — was `GitSHA != ""`.] WHY two-step not one: replay's PRE-run
    check (replay.go:121) is only `!= ""`, but the actual SHA FORMAT is enforced later
    at worktree.Checkout -> validateSHA (worktree.go:148-158: non-empty, no leading '-',
    40 or 64 chars, all lowercase hex -> ErrInvalidSHA). runmanifest.Validate
    (manifest.go:276) ALSO only requires non-empty and never checks format
    (manifest.go:302 isHexOID is applied to ReplayOf.Commit, NOT stage.GitSHA). So a
    stored manifest CAN carry a malformed git_sha, and such a run is un-replayable (it
    dies at checkout). SelectCohort's contract is "never hand .2 a qualified-but-
    un-replayable run", so the predicate must validate the format here.
 3. every input `Storage == artifactstore.StorageContent` (pointer inputs rejected at
    replay.go:163 ReadContent -> SkipPointerInput; first offending input named in Detail),
 4. output `Storage == artifactstore.StorageContent` (so .2 can read it as an eval
    target; pointer output -> SkipPointerOutput).
`runmanifest.Validate` already guarantees a structurally valid output ArtifactRef, so
no "missing output" reason is needed — only the content-vs-pointer check is meaningful.

NOT over-strict: a syntactically-invalid sha is NEVER replayable (worktree.Checkout's
validateSHA rejects it before any agent runs), so skipping it only excludes runs replay
would itself fail on. This tightens the predicate from replay's loose pre-check to what
replay can REALLY execute.

**Git-sha validity helper (decision: reimplement locally, option (a)):**
runmanifest has an unexported `isHexOID` (manifest.go:302-304) implementing exactly
"non-empty, all lowercase hex, 40 or 64 chars" — but it is UNEXPORTED, so bench cannot
import it. Add a tiny package-local `isValidGitSHA(string) bool` in cohort.go (len 40 or
64, all lowercase hex). PRECEDENT: internal/eval/result.go:342 re-implements its own
`isHexOID` (and :355 `validSHA256`) locally rather than depending on unexported
runmanifest helpers; worktree.go:148 validateSHA does the same. Implementer MUST NOT
attempt to import runmanifest.isHexOID. (Leading-'-' guard is unnecessary here — bench
does no exec; the hex+length check already excludes '-'.)

**Ordering + N:**
- Order Selected by `Created` DESC; tie-break `RunID` DESC (string compare) for
  determinism on equal timestamps. (`run list` happens to list refname-sorted; we sort
  explicitly so order is independent of enumeration.)
- `last <= 0` -> ErrInvalidLast (return zero CohortResult). Caller (.4) decides default.
- `last` larger than qualifying count -> return ALL qualifying (no error, no padding).
- Filtering/skip classification happens over ALL runs first; truncation to `last`
  applies only to Selected. Skipped is the full set (so .4 can report total skipped).

**Errors:**
- Zero runs in repo: `store.List` returns empty -> return empty CohortResult, nil
  (NOT an error; matches run.go:78 "no runs found" being non-fatal; .4 decides UX).
- Manifest fails to parse / ReadFile fails: ERROR OUT naming the run, mirroring
  run list (run.go:88-93 `fmt.Errorf("run %q: %w", id, err)`). A corrupt store is a
  real fault, not a skippable run.
- Zero QUALIFYING runs (runs exist but none eligible): return empty-but-valid
  CohortResult (Selected empty, Skipped populated), nil. The CLI bead turns this into
  its own user-facing error; SelectCohort stays policy-free.
- Exported sentinel: `ErrInvalidLast = errors.New("last must be positive")`.

